0. Retrieving the Data Frame and Cleaning (YouTube Data API v3)¶

Several packages are being installed:

The code starts by installing the google-api-python-client library, which allows the usage of various Google APIs. This library is being upgraded to ensure the latest version is installed.

Next, the youtube-dl package is installed. This package facilitates the downloading of videos from different websites, including YouTube.

The textblob package is being installed. This package provides a simple API for performing common natural language processing (NLP) tasks, such as sentiment analysis.

Moreover, the wordcloud package is installed. This package allows the creation of word clouds, which are visual representations of text data.

Lastly, the code installs the pandas and nltk packages. The nltk package is being used for tokenization, which is the process of breaking text into individual words or tokens (Arcila et al., 2022).

The sklearn library (Arcila et al., 2022), which stands for Scikit-learn. Other modules are also included, such as: the googleapiclient.discovery module, the build function is imported. It allows the creation of a service object for interacting with Google APIs (Author, Year). From the collections module, the Counter class is imported. In order to search for videos of BBC News and CNN, the function search_videos takes a channel_id parameter representing the unique identifier of the YouTube channel. It also initializes an empty list videos and sets the initial value of next_page_token to an empty string (YouTube Data API, n.d.).

Moreover, a loop is then executed to retrieve videos from the specified channel until a maximum of 500 videos have been collected from each channel by making a request to the YouTube API. The information includes the number of views, likes, publication date, title, and description of each video.

Finally, the retrieved video information is then organized into a dictionary format and appended to the videos list.

In [ ]:
# Use the search method to search for videos from the BBC News and CNN YouTube channels (retrieved from: https://developers.google.com/youtube/v3):
def search_videos(channel_id):
    try:
        videos = []
        next_page_token = ''
        while len(videos) < 500:
            search_response = youtube.search().list(
                q='',
                type='video',
                part='id,snippet',
                channelId=channel_id,
                maxResults=100,
                pageToken=next_page_token
            ).execute()

            video_ids = [search_result['id']['videoId'] for search_result in search_response.get('items', [])]
            video_stats_response = youtube.videos().list(
                part='statistics',
                id=','.join(video_ids),
                maxResults=100
            ).execute()

            for search_result, stats_result in zip(search_response.get('items', []), video_stats_response.get('items', [])):
                video = {
                    'channel': search_result['snippet']['channelTitle'],
                    'id': search_result['id']['videoId'],
                    'title': search_result['snippet']['title'],
                    'views': stats_result['statistics']['viewCount'],
                    'likes': stats_result['statistics']['likeCount'],
                    'publishedAt': search_result['snippet']['publishedAt'],
                    'description': search_result['snippet']['description']
                }
                videos.append(video)

                if len(videos) == 500:
                    break

            next_page_token = search_response.get('nextPageToken', '')

            if not next_page_token:
                break

        return videos
    except HttpError as e:
        print('An HTTP error %d occurred:\n%s' % (e.resp.status, e.content))
        return None

1. Cleaning and Creating Sentiment Classifier¶

1.1 Cleaning¶

This section addresses the cleaning and preprocessing of the data by preparing the 'title' and 'description' columns of the DataFrame 'df'. The resulting cleaned and preprocessed data is stored in a new DataFrame named 'cleaned_df'.

The code initially creates a copy of the original DataFrame 'df' to maintain the original dataset. Noise in the form of specific characters or strings, such as "'" and ""Boom"", is removed from the 'title' and 'description' columns by replacing them with empty strings. Moreover, in order to handle missing values, any NaN values in the 'title' and 'description' columns are replaced with empty strings.

Additionally, the code then cleans, such as removing 'stopwords' and spaces, the text in the 'title' and 'description' columns separately. The NLTK library is used to access a set of English stopwords. Each text in the 'title' and 'description' columns is tokenized into individual words. This results in the 'cleaned_df' DataFrame and is ready for sentiment analysis.

In [26]:
cleaned_df = df.copy()

# Leaving out noise in the 'title' and 'description' columns
cleaned_df['title'] = cleaned_df['title'].str.replace("&#39;", "")
cleaned_df['description'] = cleaned_df['description'].str.replace("&#39;", "")
cleaned_df['title'] = cleaned_df['title'].str.replace("&quot;Boom&quot;", "")
cleaned_df['description'] = cleaned_df['description'].str.replace("&quot;Boom&quot;", "")

# Replacing the NaN values in 'description' column with an empty string
cleaned_df['description'] = cleaned_df['description'].fillna('')

# Replacing the NaN values in 'description' column with an empty string
cleaned_df['title'] = cleaned_df['title'].fillna('')

# Cleaning and preprocess the 'title' column
cleaned_df['title_cleaned'] = cleaned_df['title'].apply(lambda x: re.sub(r'[^\w\s]', '', x.lower()))

# Cleaning and preprocess the 'description' column
cleaned_df['description_cleaned'] = cleaned_df['description'].apply(lambda x: re.sub(r'[^\w\s]', '', str(x).lower()))

# Removing stopwords from 'title' column
stopwords_set = set(stopwords.words('english'))
cleaned_df['title_cleaned'] = cleaned_df['title_cleaned'].apply(lambda x: ' '.join([word for word in word_tokenize(x) if word not in stopwords_set]))

# Removing stopwords from 'description' column
cleaned_df['description_cleaned'] = cleaned_df['description_cleaned'].apply(lambda x: ' '.join([word for word in word_tokenize(x) if word not in stopwords_set]))

1.2 Creating Sentiment Classifier¶

In order to create a sentiment classifier, there are a couple of steps to be made:

Firstly, SentimentIntensityAnalyzer named 'sia' is created in order to calculate scores for text data. The sentiment analysis is then applied to the 'title' and 'description' columns.

The lambda function calls the 'polarity_scores' of 'sia' on each value in the 'title_cleaned' and 'description_cleaned' columns. This method returns a dictionary of sentiment scores, and the 'compound' score (representing overall sentiment) is extracted and stored in a new column called 'title_sentiment' and 'description_sentiment.'

To categorize the sentiment scores into positive, negative, or neutral categories, two additional columns are created: 'sentiment_category_title' and 'sentiment_category_description'. Here the lambda function assigns the appropriate sentiment category ('Positive', 'Negative', or 'Neutral') based on the score conditions: greater than 0 for positive, less than 0 for negative, and otherwise neutral.

In [28]:
#Sentiment classifier

# Create a SentimentIntensityAnalyzer object
sia = SentimentIntensityAnalyzer()

# Applying a sentiment analysis on the 'title' column
cleaned_df['title_sentiment'] = cleaned_df['title_cleaned'].apply(lambda x: sia.polarity_scores(x)['compound'])

# Applying a sentiment analysis on the 'description' column
cleaned_df['description_sentiment'] = cleaned_df['description_cleaned'].apply(lambda x: sia.polarity_scores(str(x))['compound'])

# Categorizizing the sentiment scores into positive, negative, or neutral
cleaned_df['sentiment_category_title'] = cleaned_df['title_sentiment'].apply(lambda x: 'Positive' if x > 0 else 'Negative' if x < 0 else 'Neutral')

# Categorizing the sentiment scores into positive, negative, or neutral
cleaned_df['sentiment_category_description'] = cleaned_df['description_sentiment'].apply(lambda x: 'Positive' if x > 0 else 'Negative' if x < 0 else 'Neutral')

The following code presents two bar plots to compare the number of views for videos belonging to the channels CNN and BBC News.

Four empty lists are created, 'cnn_likes' 'bbc_likes', 'cnn_views' and 'bbc_views', which are used to store the number of views for each video in the channels. Next, a loop iterates over each row in the 'cleaned_df' DataFrame using the 'iterrows()' function. Additionally, the number of views is extracted from the 'views' column and converted to an integer. Furthermore, an if-else statement checks the 'channel' value of the row.

These similar steps have also been taken in order to examine the number of likes for each videos.

In [9]:
# Creating a list of views for each channel (retrieved from: https://www.python-graph-gallery.com)
cnn_views = []
cnn_likes = []
bbc_views = []
bbc_likes = []

for index, row in cleaned_df.iterrows():
    views = int(row['views'])
    likes = int(row['likes'])
    if row['channel'] == 'CNN':
        cnn_views.append(views)
        cnn_likes.append(likes)
    elif row['channel'] == 'BBC News':
        bbc_views.append(views)
        bbc_likes.append(likes)

The next exploratory examination concerns a word frequency analysis on the titles and descriptions of CNN and BBC News videos. It uses the Counter class from the collections module to count the occurrences of each word and retrieves the top 25 most mentioned words for each channel. It combines the cleaned titles and descriptions into separate strings, 'bbc_text' and 'cnn_text', by selecting the corresponding rows from the DataFrame.

To calculate the word frequencies, the text strings are split into individual words and passed to the Counter class, which counts the occurrences of each word. The top 25 most common words and their frequencies are stored in 'bbc_top_words' and 'cnn_top_words' variables for BBC News and CNN, respectively.

Finally, the code prints the top 25 words and their frequencies for each channel, providing insights into the most frequently used words in the cleaned titles and descriptions of BBC News and CNN.

In [11]:
bbc_text = ' '.join(cleaned_df[cleaned_df['channel'] == 'BBC News']['title_cleaned'] + cleaned_df[cleaned_df['channel'] == 'BBC News']['description_cleaned'])
cnn_text = ' '.join(cleaned_df[cleaned_df['channel'] == 'CNN']['title_cleaned'] + cleaned_df[cleaned_df['channel'] == 'CNN']['description_cleaned'])

# Get word frequencies for BBC News
bbc_word_freq = Counter(bbc_text.split())
# Get the top 25 words and frequencies
bbc_top_words = bbc_word_freq.most_common(25)

# Get word frequencies for CNN
cnn_word_freq = Counter(cnn_text.split())
# Get the top 25 words and frequencies
cnn_top_words = cnn_word_freq.most_common(25)

# Print the top 25 words and frequencies for BBC News
print("Top 25 words in BBC News:")
for word, frequency in bbc_top_words:
    print(f"{word}: {frequency}")

# Print the top 25 words and frequencies for CNN
print("\nTop 25 words in CNN:")
for word, frequency in cnn_top_words:
    print(f"{word}: {frequency}")

3. Sentiment Analysis¶

In order to answer the following research question:

RQ: To what extent can sentiment analysis be used to predict view count of news on YouTube?

This research shall evaluate 3 models:

Firstly, the sentiment form title is used as a categorical variable to predict view count as the dependant variable. Moreover, the 'sentiment_category_title' and 'sentiment_category_description' columns are one-hot encoded using the OneHotEncoder class from scikit-learn. This process converts the categorical data into a binary representation that can be used for modeling.The resulting encoded categories are stored in the 'categories_df' DataFrame. Next, the encoded categories are concatenated with the original DataFrame 'df' using pd.concat(), resulting in the 'df_encoded' DataFrame. This combines the original features with the encoded sentiment categories.

Secondly, the same is conducted, but implements the sentiments from the descriptions as a means to predict engagement. The features ('X') and the target variable ('y') are defined. The features are extracted from the column names of the 'categories_df', and the target variable is set to 'likes'. Furthermore, the data is then split into training and test sets using train_test_split() from scikit-learn. The 'X_train' and 'y_train' variables contain the training features and target values, respectively, while 'X_test' and 'y_test' hold the corresponding test data.

Finally, given the potentially more complex relationship between the variables as well as their types, this paper also uses a multiple regression model and tests it for accuracy, as this one might be more robust than the previous ones. In order to realize this, a linear regression model is trained using the LinearRegression() class from scikit-learn. The model is fitted on the training data using the fit() method. Based on the predict() method, predictions are made.

The aim of the sentiment analysis was to observe whether one can predict the number of likes and views based on the sentiment category of the title and descriptions of a dataset using a linear regression model. However, the following tests show that the sentiment analysis cannot be used in order to predict view count of news on YouTube. Therefore, the research question concludes with: untill this degree, these models do not effectively predict view count based on a sentiment analysis.

In [14]:
# Sentiment predicting views based on sentiment title (Retrieved from: https://scikit-learn/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.preprocessing.OneHotEncoder.html)

# Perform one-hot encoding on the 'sentiment_category' column
one_hot_encoder = OneHotEncoder(sparse=False)
encoded_categories = one_hot_encoder.fit_transform(cleaned_df['sentiment_category_title'].values.reshape(-1, 1))
categories_df = pd.DataFrame(encoded_categories, columns=one_hot_encoder.categories_[0])

# Concatenate the encoded categories with the original DataFrame
df_encoded = pd.concat([df, categories_df], axis=1)

# Define the features (X) and target variable (y)
features = categories_df.columns.tolist()
target = 'views'

# Split the data into training and test sets
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(df_encoded[features], df_encoded[target], test_size=0.2, random_state=42)

# Train a linear regression model
model = LinearRegression()
model.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Make predictions on the test set
y_pred = model.predict(X_test)

# Evaluate the model
mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred)
r2 = r2_score(y_test, y_pred)

print(f"Mean Squared Error (MSE): {mse:.2f}")
print(f"R-squared (R2) Score: {r2:.2f}")

Mean Squared Error (MSE): 1439766912860.85
R-squared (R2) Score: -0.01

one_hot_encoder = OneHotEncoder(sparse=False)
encoded_categories = one_hot_encoder.fit_transform(cleaned_df['sentiment_category_description'].values.reshape(-1, 1))
categories_df = pd.DataFrame(encoded_categories, columns=one_hot_encoder.categories_[0])

# Concatenate the encoded categories with the original DataFrame
df_encoded = pd.concat([df, categories_df], axis=1)

# Define the features (X) and target variable (y)
features = categories_df.columns.tolist()
target = 'views'

# Split the data into training and test sets
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(df_encoded[features], df_encoded[target], test_size=0.2, random_state=42)

# Train a linear regression model
model = LinearRegression()
model.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Make predictions on the test set
y_pred = model.predict(X_test)

# Evaluate the model
mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred)
r2 = r2_score(y_test, y_pred)

print(f"Mean Squared Error (MSE): {mse:.2f}")
print(f"R-squared (R2) Score: {r2:.2f}")

Despite the fact that the three models do not seem to support the notion that sentiment analysis can be used for predicting viewcounts on YouTube, a visual comparison is created of the distribution of sentiment categories between the two news channels.

It filters the DataFrame df to create two separate DataFrames, bbc_df and cnn_df, containing data only from the 'BBC News' and 'CNN' channels, respectively. Furthermore, the number of occurrences is counted of each sentiment category in the 'sentiment_category_description' and 'sentiment_category_title' column for the 'BBC News' and 'CNN' channels, storing the counts in cnn_sentiment_counts and bbc_sentiment_counts. In addition, the proportion of each sentiment category is calculated and divides the sentiment score by the sum of all counts.

In [57]:
# Filter the DataFrame for 'BBC News' and 'CNN' channels separately (Retrieved from: https://www.python-graph-gallery.com/)
bbc_df = cleaned_df[df['channel'] == 'BBC News']
cnn_df = cleaned_df[df['channel'] == 'CNN']

# Counting the number of each sentiment category for 'BBC News'
bbc_sentiment_counts = bbc_df['sentiment_category_description'].value_counts()

# Counting the number of each sentiment category for 'CNN'
cnn_sentiment_counts = cnn_df['sentiment_category_description'].value_counts()

# Calculate the proportion of each sentiment category for 'BBC News'
bbc_sentiment_proportions = bbc_sentiment_counts / bbc_sentiment_counts.sum()

# Calculate the proportion of each sentiment category for 'CNN'
cnn_sentiment_proportions = cnn_sentiment_counts / cnn_sentiment_counts.sum()

# Create a DataFrame for the proportions of sentiment categories
sentiment_df = pd.DataFrame({
    'BBC News': bbc_sentiment_proportions,
    'CNN': cnn_sentiment_proportions
})

# Plot the stacked bar plot
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
sns.set_palette(['blue', 'red'])  # Set the colors for BBC News and CNN respectively
sentiment_df.plot(kind='bar', stacked=True)
plt.title('Sentiment Categories Comparison: BBC News vs CNN')
plt.xlabel('Sentiment Category')
plt.ylabel('Proportion')
plt.legend(title='Channels')
plt.show()
